Effects of Temperature and Wind on Arrival Time of Trans-Gulf Migrants

Gone-Fishing

2022-12-15

Introduction

The term trans-Gulf migrants or TGMs, refer to species of birds that fly non-stop over the Gulf of Mexico and arrive on land between Texas and Florida. They are part of a larger group of birds that undertake long-distance migrations from Central and South America to more temperate latitudes.

The time of arrival of these TGMs have quite a large effect on their rates of survival. One example of this is the red knot, or Calidris canutus rufa. In the spring, this species of bird travels from Tierra del Fuego to the Delaware Bay (a 30,000 km trip), and usually bulks up on horseshoe crab eggs in Delaware Bay before leaving to breed in Arctic polar deserts. From 1997-2002, a higher proportion of knots did not reach threshold departure masses, and the population size dropped from 51,000 to 37,000. This drop in population is assumed to be a result of birds arriving later in Delaware, after the horseshoe crab eggs had already been depleted. (Baker et al. (2004))

Other research has also shown that survival rates are reduced by cold weather and high density, (Cook et al. (2021)) and as climate change continues to cause abnormal temperature and weather fluctuation, TGM survival rate also fluctuates.

In 2002, Cornell Laboratory of Ornithology and the National Audubon society created a program called eBird that allows citizen scientists and birders to share their observations, creating a database for bird sightings. The creation of this program has the potential to be an incredibly important tool in the study of avian biology.

Our goal with this project is to use eBird and meteorological data to understand the effect of local weather conditions when TGMs arrive in Massachusetts.

Methods

First we chose five trans-Gulf migrant (TGM) bird species to study, each bird species being from different families. The species we chose are as follows: Common Nighthawk (Chordeiles minor), Scarlet Tanager (Piranga olivacea), Cerulean Warbler (Setophaga cerulea), Baltimore Oriole (Icterus galbula), and Red-eyed vireo (Vireo olivaceus). Using the occ_data() function from rgbif, which searches GBIF occurrences, we then download the occurrence data for these species. We then used logistic modeling operations to predict the Julian day when 25% of the population arrives, aka the arrival time, for each year and for each species. Three locations were chosen along the assumed flight path of the birds, Mobile, AL being on the Gulf at the beginning of the route, Boston, MA being the end destination, and Charlotte, NC being about the middle of the journey. We used weather data from the NOAA website with the parameters of minimum and maximum temperature in tenths of degrees celsius (tmin), average wind velocity in m/s (awnd), and direction of fastest 2-minute wind (wdf2). To evaluate the effect of weather parameters on arrival time we used a linear mixed-effect modeling using lme4 package and lme4() function. Lastly we use the anova() function from the car package to look at the interactions and assesses the significance of the fixed effects.

Discussion

Through utilizing meteorological and eBird data, the effect of temporal conditions on TGM arrival in Massachusetts were explained upon conducting various linear mixed-effect modeling. In terms of how arrival time varies according to temperature and wind variables, majority of the 5 species analyzed show a general trend of earlier arrival dates since 2000. One notable exception is Setophaga cerulea, where a positive correlation can be observed on the year vs.Julian day graph.

Through linear mixed-effect modeling, the best-fit model identified was with j.day~wk.tmin+wk.tmax+wk.wvec+(1|name), that is, with no interaction effect included between any of the variables. It was also found that wind vector best explains the trend in all except 1 of the 5 species, namely Icterus galbula. Maximum temperature was the only factor that was found to be a significant predictor of arrival time Icterus galbula. Minimum temperature was also found to best explain the data for species Chordeiles minor, Piranga olivacea, and Setophaga cerulea.

From these results, it can be reasonable assumed that climate change will, if not already has, played a role in the population status of TGMs arriving in MA during the spring. The graphs approximating annual arrival time for 25% of the species population to arrive in MA shown that most species are arriving earlier than expected, with times ranging somewhere around 5 to 10 days earlier. Higher global temperatures result in a significant shift in migratory patterns in both short- and long-distance migrants, a finding that contradicts the claims of previous studies suggesting that short-distance migrants in North America are changing their migration patterns more than long-distance migrants (SOURCE 1). Rapid adaptation to the changing climate can be beneficial in the sense that it can decrease population declines by finding alternative grounds and/or staying in suitable areas for a longer period of time to breed and find food (SOURCE 1). However, not all species react the same way to temperature changes and those that have been unsuccessful in shifting their migration patterns are likely to see a population decline over time.

In terms of the role that climatic variables play in long-distance migration of birds, previous studies have confirmed that wind vector, specifically tail-winds, are taken into account by long-distance migrants; tail-winds are considered a vital support for long-distance migrants to cover the extensive area that they do (SOURCE 2). This explains why we found that wind vector was a significant predictor of arrival time in nearly all of the species.

Discussion

Through utilizing meteorological and eBird data, the effect of temporal conditions on TGM arrival in Massachusetts were explained upon conducting various linear mixed-effect modeling. In terms of how arrival time varies according to temperature and wind variables, majority of the 5 species analyzed show a general trend of earlier arrival dates since 2000. One notable exception is Setophaga cerulea, where a positive correlation can be observed on the year vs.Julian day graph.

Through linear mixed-effect modeling, the best-fit model identified was with j.day~wk.tmin+wk.tmax+wk.wvec+(1|name), that is, with no interaction effect included between any of the variables. It was also found that wind vector best explains the trend in all except 1 of the 5 species, namely Icterus galbula. Maximum temperature was the only factor that was found to be a significant predictor of arrival time Icterus galbula. Minimum temperature was also found to best explain the data for species Chordeiles minor, Piranga olivacea, and Setophaga cerulea.

From these results, it can be reasonable assumed that climate change will, if not already has, played a role in the population status of TGMs arriving in MA during the spring. The graphs approximating annual arrival time for 25% of the species population to arrive in MA shown that most species are arriving earlier than expected, with times ranging somewhere around 5 to 10 days earlier. Higher global temperatures result in a significant shift in migratory patterns in both short- and long-distance migrants, a finding that contradicts the claims of previous studies suggesting that short-distance migrants in North America are changing their migration patterns more than long-distance migrants (Zaifman et al. (2017)). Rapid adaptation to the changing climate can be beneficial in the sense that it can decrease population declines by finding alternative grounds and/or staying in suitable areas for a longer period of time to breed and find food (Zaifman et al. (2017)). However, not all species react the same way to temperature changes and those that have been unsuccessful in shifting their migration patterns are likely to see a population decline over time.

In terms of the role that climatic variables play in long-distance migration of birds, previous studies have confirmed that wind vector, specifically tail-winds, are taken into account by long-distance migrants; tail-winds are considered a vital support for long-distance migrants to cover the extensive area that they do (Liechti (2006)). This explains why we found that wind vector was a significant predictor of arrival time in nearly all of the species.
